[1] Australia (North Queensland)
Date: Thu 25 Feb 2010
Source: Couriermail.com.au [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26772394-3102,00.html?>


A locally acquired case of dengue fever has been reported in the
north Queensland town of Tully -- the 1st in the town in at least 2
decades, Queensland Health says. Townsville has also recorded 13
locally acquired cases of the potentially deadly mosquito-borne
disease in 2 separate outbreaks this season.

Queensland Health medical director Jeffrey Hanna said a Dengue Action
Response Team would visit Tully to undertake yard inspections and set
traps for dengue mosquitoes. "Dengue mosquitoes only breed around
homes and in urban areas ... not in swamps or creeks," he said.
Common dengue mosquito breeding sites include tyres, buckets, toys,
and pot plant bases.

"With the recent rains and the warm temperatures, I strongly urge all
Tully residents to take preventive steps," Dr Hanna said. "It is
important that people -- individuals, as well as businesses -- get
rid of mosquito breeding sites around the yard and workplace."

[Byline: Janelle Miles]

--
