[2] Bolivia (Santa Cruz)
Date: Tue 23 Feb 2010
Source: El Mundo [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.elmundo.com.bo/Secundarianew.asp?edicion=23/02/2010&Tipo=Comunidad&Cod=12209>


Departmental Health Service authorities (SEDES), declared an orange
alert following the death of a young man of 26 years with severe
dengue fever, and the rise of suspected cases as a result of the
weather conditions. Ervin Saucedo, director of SEDES, reported that
the city of Santa Cruz confirmed 24 [dengue] cases of the 246
suspected cases; in the municipality of Yapacani, 5 cases were
confirmed. There is also a major outbreak in relation to last year
[2009] in the border area of Mato Grosso do Sul [state] in Brazil.

"We again urge people to continue collaborating with cleanup to avoid
mosquito breeding sites in old tires and trash in the open," he urged.

Saucedo said the man's death, which is still under investigation, was
due to a severe dengue [virus] type 2 [infection], which along with
[dengue virus] serotypes 1 and 3 may be circulating in Santa Cruz
given that weather conditions are propitious for the proliferation of
the mosquito.

"This [dengue virus] serotype is highly lethal because of a
combination of 2 factors, which can make this severe dengue
[infection] lead to death. We are facing a clinical complication and
that is why we are undertaking a series of activities," he said.

For his part, the director of SEDES recalled that this period is one
of high risk, because in March the rains intensify and, combined with
the heat, the development of larvae and [adult] mosquitoes is
accelerated, which can cause an outbreak of important proportions. To
avoid this, severe measures will be taken.

[Byline: Shirley Pizarro Davalos]

--
