[3] Brazil (national)
Date: Sat 27 Feb 2010
Source: Google News, Agencia EFE report [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.google.com/hostednews/epa/article/ALeqM5jX9WNCWogBi7zfUZRa4gtyqkJz4A>


The Brazilian state of Goias and 4 others that border Bolivia have a
concentration of 71 percent of the dengue cases registered in Brazil
during the 1st 6 weeks of the year [2010] and which have issued an
alert in the northwest region of the country, the Ministry of Health
announced today [27 Feb 2010]. Rondonia, Mato Grosso do Sul, Acre,
Mato Grosso, all bordering Bolivia, and Goias are the states which
record the highest dengue incidence in Brazil with indices between
423.2 and 891.7 cases per 100 000 population, a scale that is
considered high when above the 300s. In absolute numbers, these 5
states record 77 117 of the 108 640 cases registered in the whole
country between 1 Jan-13 Feb [2010].

Despite a doubling of the number of [dengue] cases from the same
period of 2009, when 51 873 cases were reported, in the 1st 6 weeks
of this year [2010], 21 deaths from the disease have been registered,
10 less than in the same period of 2009.

The concentration of the disease along the border with Bolivia was
confirmed after the vice minister of Health of the Andean country,
Nila Heredia, stated that the new strain [serotype] of dengue [virus]
which has been detected in Bolivian territory may have come from Brazil.

--
