[4] Brazil (Sao Paulo and national)
Date: Fri 26 Feb 2010
Source: Folha Online [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u699582.shtml>


Data from the CVE (Center for Epidemiological Surveillance) of the
Secretariat of Health of Sao Paulo reveal that the number of dengue
cases in the state between 1 Jan and last Wednesday [24 Feb 2010] has
reached 7594, which represents an 84 percent of the total [recorded]
for 2009, when 8996 [dengue virus] infections were confirmed. In the
same period of last year [2009] (in 6 weeks) there were 771 [dengue
virus] infections, according to SUCEN (Superintendency of Control of
Endemics), which represents an increase of 885 percent.

Despite the increase, the SUCEN superintendent, Affonso Viviani,
denied that there is an imminent [dengue] epidemic in Sao Paulo, but
issued an alert of risk for dengue spread mainly in the
municipalities of the western region, such as Ribeirao Preto, Sao
Jose do Rio Preto, and Aracatuba. "At the moment, there is not a
picture that signals a dengue epidemic in Sao Paulo, because this
depends on the number people in the state. But some cities in the
western region, and Guaruja (Baixada Santista) already have
transmission indices compatible with a risk of epidemic," he stated
to Folha Online.

SUCEN is responsible for a mega operation to combat the mosquito that
transmits the disease [virus], _Aedes aegypti_, initiated this Friday
[26 Feb 2010]. Altogether, more than 10 000 agents participate in the
preventive action, which was anticipated this year [2010] due to the
heat and above average rainfall recorded since the beginning of the
year [2010]. The index of above average rainfall is noted by the
superintendent of the municipal government as one of the reasons for
the increase in the number of cases in the state.

Another factor that helped boost the number of cases is the
recirculation of dengue [virus] type 1, which did not prevail in the
state for more than a decade. "The objective of this [control]
campaign is to reinforce the necessity of elimination of breeding
sites of the dengue mosquito. The greatest infestation occurs from
March, and the only way to reduce dengue is to eliminate the breeding
[sites] of the mosquito, "said Viviani. He said that only in the city
of Sao Paulo 30 cases of the disease were confirmed, of which just 3
were in Bristol Park, in the southern area of the city, a locale
supervised during the [control] blitz today [27 Feb 2010] by the
Secretariat of Health.

All together, 28 deaths are being investigated in the state, with
another 2 cases now confirmed -- one in Mirassolandia and another in
Sao Jose do Rio Preto, reported Viviani to SUCEN.

According to the Ministry of Health, in the 1st 6 weeks of this year
[2010], the number of dengue cases increased more than 100 percent in
relation to 2009. Between 1 Jan-13 Feb [2010], 106 640 [dengue] cases
have been recorded in the whole country, versus 51 873 last year [2009].

The numbers from CVE (which may be changed according to the daily
data of confirmations from the municipalities), however, differ from
those announced today [26 Feb 2010] by the Ministry of Health, which
noted that there were 2930 confirmed cases of the disease in Sao
Paulo (in 6 weeks), compared to 425 registered in the same period
last year [2009] -- an increase of 589.4 percent. This [difference]
is because Sao Paulo state counts confirmed cases up to the last day,
24 Feb [2010], whereas the Ministry of Health presents data up to 13
[Feb 2010]. That, according to the Secretariat, accounts for the difference.

