[5] Brazil (Rio Grande do Sul)
Date: Mon 22 Feb 2010
Source: Gazetaweb, Folha Online report [in Portuguese, trans. & summ.
Mod.TY, edited]
<http://gazetaweb.globo.com/v2/noticias/texto_completo.php?c=197575>


Dengue returns to RS [Rio Grande do Sul] after 3 years without
recorded cases. Although the number of cases is small relative to
other regions, the resurgence of dengue is worrying. After almost 3
years without registering dengue cases, Rio Grande do Sul is facing a
new epidemic of the disease.

In Ijui (402 km [250 mi] from Porto Alegre), 11 people have now
contracted the disease, according to the state Center for Health
Surveillance). The state authorities are now treating the case of
Ijui, a municipality of 80 000 inhabitants, as a dengue outbreak
because it has registered a large number of cases in a small
geographic region. "The 1st tests indicated that this is dengue
fever, but there is already an epidemic reality because dozens of
people with [dengue-like] symptoms sought [attention by the] health
network of the city during the weekend [20-21 Feb 2010]," said the
director of the state center, Francisco Paz. The determination of the
type of dengue [virus] still depends on the results of tests with are
being done by the Instituto Adolfo Lutz in Sao Paulo.

Although the number of [dengue] cases in RS is small in relation to
other regions of the country, the resurgence of dengue in Rio Grande
do Sul worries the Ministry of Health because, while they are not
dealing with a common disease in the state, the majority of
[individuals in] the population have not developed antibodies against
the virus. "There is an alert situation because the majority of
[individuals] in the population have never had contact with the
disease [virus]," said the Coordinator of the National Dengue Control
Program of the Ministry of Health, Giovanini Coelho. He said that as
there is no vaccine, all that can be done is to combat the vector
(_Aedes aegypti_) so that [dengue does] not spread between the
regions, as well as strengthening [medical] assistance to those who
develop symptoms.

The health authorities as well as specialists in epidemiology
consider that a combination of climatic factors, which benefit the
proliferation of mosquitoes, with the circulation of virus by
visitors who have had contact with [dengue] foci in RS, is the most
probable cause for the return of the disease.

According to the private meteorological service, MetSul, the
temperature this summer is around 4 deg [C, 7 deg F] above the
historical mean for February in many regions of the state. The hot
temperatures, in combination with a rainy period that in some cities
has brought 3 times more rainfall in relation to historical averages,
has boosted mosquito breeding. According to the state Secretariat of
Health, _Aedes aegypti_ has now been found in 53 of the 496 RS municipalities.

"If the virus arrives in a region that has the vector, an epidemic
can occur, especially if the population has not had previous massive
exposure to the disease [virus] and has not developed immunity,"
stated Jose Evoide de Moura, epidemiologist at the UnB (University of
Brasilia).

--
