[6] Brazil (Mato Grosso do Sul)
Date: Tue 23 Feb 2010
Source: O Jornal [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.cassilandiajornal.com.br/index.php?p=noticias&id=1382&ed_id=10>


An outbreak of dengue has killed 9 people in the [state] capital.
From official statistics, the severity of the dengue epidemic has
frightening numbers. While SESAU (municipal Secretariat of Health)
confirms one death in Campo Grande, 8 others died of the disease.

Just in the San Juliao Hospital, which since January [2010] has 20
beds for care for patients with dengue, 4 deaths were recorded.
According to infectious disease physician, Mauricio Pompilio,
referring to the disease in the state, 3 died in San Julian and one
was transferred to the CTI (Intensive Care Center) of HU (Regional
Hospital), where he died. "The youngest patient was 56 years, others
were older than 60 years." The doctor explained that in all cases the
clinical picture (symptoms) was dengue, but to enter the official
statistics of the disease, serology tests are necessary, the results
of which are sent to health secretariats.

After the outbreak, which recorded 45 000 cases and 2 deaths in 2007,
one death from dengue was officially registered in 2010, in Campo
Grande. However, adding the deaths in Sao Juliao, plus the confirmed
case and those under investigation, the total reaches 9 deaths.

SESAU investigated the death of a 22 year-old after being attended in
the UPA (Emergency Care Unit of Vila Almeida), a woman of 67 years
who was admitted to the HR (Regional Hospital) Rosa Pedrossian, and a
man of 75 years. There is a 4th death, a woman of 83 years, who died
of DHF in the Campo Grande Clinic. Last year [2009], a child of 7
years and an adolescent of 13 years died of suspected dengue.

In Santa Casa [?hospital] 9 people have been admitted with dengue. Of
that total, 7 patients presented with DHF; 5 children and 2 adults.
No deaths were registered.

Since January [2010], dengue has caused hospital admission of 169
people. Santa Casa and HR provide references for admissions of
children in serious condition.

The infectious disease physician Mauricio Pompilio emphasizes that
people must seek medical attention when they experience the 1st
dengue symptoms. The disease causes fever, headache, body ache, and
loss of appetite.

According the SESAU bulletin, as of yesterday [22 Feb 2010] Campo
Grande had a total of 14 202 dengue cases.

--
