[7] Paraguay
Date: Wed 24 Feb 2010
Source: Ultima Hora [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.ultimahora.com/notas/299350-Dengue:-Nueva-cepa-aumenta-posibilidades-de--casos-graves>


The Ministry of Public Health (MSP), in a statement by Dr Julio Cesar
Manzur, director of the National Vector-Transmitted Diseases Service
(SENEPA), has confirmed the circulation of 3 types of dengue [virus]
(with the arrival of [dengue virus] serotype 2) in the country, which
increases the probabilities of the appearance of serious dengue
[disease], previously termed DHF. When a region has 2 or more [dengue
virus] serotypes [circulating] at the same time, it turns into an
area of hyperendemicity. "A hyperendemic area is characterized as
such because there is more virus circulation and among them more
virulent strains might appear. This is a great public health menace,"
he said. According to Manzur, it has been shown that with an
increasing number of mild cases -- that is as the epidemic grows --
more serious cases begin to appear as well. "The greater the
appearance of mild forms [of the infection], more serious forms
appear also," he added. and pointed out that severe forms of dengue
can be caused by whichever of the 3 [dengue virus] serotypes (1,2, or
3) is circulating in the country.

There are various factors included in the appearance of serious
cases. "In the 1st place, the predisposition of the patient. Every
person reacts in a different way to the virus attack. In 2nd place,
if the person has been infected by a given [dengue virus] serotype,
when they are infected by a 2nd serotype, the probability of
development of serious dengue is greater," he noted. "That is why, he
added, it is best to cut short an outbreak which could hit a specific
city or in a specific department [state of province equivalent]," he
pointed out.

The past [1 Feb 2010], the Ministry of Public Health declared an
epidemiological alert as a result of the detection of dengue virus
serotype 2 (DEN-2) in the country. The discovery was made in patients
resident in the department of Amambay. The declaration of the alert
signaled that the introduction of this new strain [virus serotype]
"implies high risk for Paraguay in case an epidemic is produced,
especially because of the risk of appearance of serious dengue cases."

The alert situation implies the activation of the departmental
contingency plans for dengue mitigation, as well as the activation of
regional rapid response teams for exhaustive investigation of
outbreaks of febrile syndromes, among other actions.

Up to now, there are 5 departments of the country with active
circulation of dengue virus. They are: Concepcion (174 cases), Alto
Parana (153), Amambay (51), Central (37), and Alto Paraguay (11),
plus the Capital (12). At the same time, the departments free of
cases are: San Pedro, Cordillera, Guaira, Caazapa, Itapua, and Neembucu.

The confirmed dengue cases in the country, since the beginning of the
current epidemic period (in November 2009), total 477, with a total
of 1653 suspected cases, according to the latest official report. Of
the confirmed [cases], 19 required hospitalization and 9 had been
classified with alarming signs. To date, no dengue-associated deaths
have been registered, according to MSP.

In Asuncion, the neighborhoods affected by dengue outbreaks are:
Banado Tacumbu, Jara, Villa Morra, Loma Pyta, Mburucuya, San
Cristobal, and Herrera.

--
